## 2.4 Bregman Divergences and Projections

### 2.4.1 Definition and Properties

Let \(\Phi\) be a strictly convex, differentiable function defined on a convex set \(\mathcal{C} \subset \mathbb{R}^n\). The **Bregman divergence** associated with \(\Phi\) is
\[
D_\Phi(p,q) = \Phi(p) - \Phi(q) - \langle \nabla \Phi(q), p - q \rangle.
\]
Bregman divergences are not symmetric in general but satisfy \(D_\Phi(p,q) \ge 0\) with equality iff \(p = q\), and they are convex in the first argument.

For \(\Phi(x) = \sum_i x_i \log x_i - x_i\) (with the convention \(0\log 0=0\)), we obtain the **Kullback–Leibler divergence**:
\[
D_{\text{KL}}(p\|q) = \sum_i p_i \log\frac{p_i}{q_i} - \sum_i p_i + \sum_i q_i.
\]
When \(p\) and \(q\) are probability vectors, the terms \(\sum p_i = \sum q_i = 1\) simplify to the familiar expression.

### 2.4.2 Bregman Projections

Given a convex set \(\mathcal{M} \subset \mathcal{C}\), the **Bregman projection** of a point \(q\) onto \(\mathcal{M}\) is the unique point \(p^* \in \mathcal{M}\) that minimizes \(D_\Phi(p,q)\) over \(p \in \mathcal{M}\). Existence and uniqueness follow from strict convexity and the closedness of \(\mathcal{M}\).

**Theorem 2.5 (Generalized Pythagorean Theorem).**  
If \(p^*\) is the Bregman projection of \(q\) onto \(\mathcal{M}\), then for any \(p \in \mathcal{M}\),
\[
D_\Phi(p,q) = D_\Phi(p,p^*) + D_\Phi(p^*,q) + \langle \nabla \Phi(p^*) - \nabla \Phi(q), p - p^* \rangle.
\]
If \(\mathcal{M}\) is a linear subspace or if the divergence satisfies the **Pythagorean identity** (true for KL divergence when \(\mathcal{M}\) is an exponential family), the last term vanishes, giving the usual Pythagoras relation.

*Proof.* This follows from the definition of Bregman divergence and the first‑order optimality condition \(\langle \nabla \Phi(p^*) - \nabla \Phi(q), p - p^* \rangle \ge 0\) for all \(p \in \mathcal{M}\). ∎

For the KL divergence, the Bregman projection onto a convex set of probability densities is the **information projection** (I‑projection). When the set is defined by linear constraints (e.g., moment conditions), the I‑projection can be obtained by solving a convex optimization problem.

### 2.4.3 Projections in Non‑commutative Setting

In the non‑commutative case, the Umegaki relative entropy \(S(\rho\|\sigma)\) plays the role of the Bregman divergence. The Bregman projection onto a convex set of states with respect to \(S\) is again unique when the set is closed and convex. For sets defined by CP maps, we will show in Chapter 4 that the NCCO corresponds to such a projection.

