## Appendix A: Schur Test and Boundedness of Integral Operators

We provide a rigorous statement and proof of the Schur test, which is used to establish boundedness of integral operators on \(L^2\). This ensures that kernels used in NCCOs yield well‑defined operators on the space of densities.

**Theorem A.1 (Schur Test).**  
Let \((\Omega, \mu)\) be a \(\sigma\)-finite measure space and let \(K: \Omega \times \Omega \to \mathbb{C}\) be a measurable kernel. Suppose there exist measurable positive functions \(p, q\) and constants \(C_1, C_2\) such that  

\[
\int |K(x,y)| \, p(y) \, d\mu(y) \le C_1 \, q(x) \quad \text{for a.e. } x,
\]  
\[
\int |K(x,y)| \, q(x) \, d\mu(x) \le C_2 \, p(y) \quad \text{for a.e. } y.
\]  

Then the integral operator \(T: L^2(\mu) \to L^2(\mu)\) defined by  
\[
(Tf)(x) = \int K(x,y) f(y) \, d\mu(y)
\]  
is bounded with \(\|T\|_{L^2 \to L^2} \le \sqrt{C_1 C_2}\).

*Proof.* Consider the factorization \(T = A B\) where \(A\) is multiplication by \(q\) and \(B\) is an operator from \(L^2\) to \(L^2\) with kernel \(\tilde{K}(x,y) = K(x,y) p(y)/q(x)\). Using the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality and the given estimates, we obtain  
\[
|(Bf)(x)|^2 = \left| \int \frac{K(x,y) p(y)}{q(x)} f(y) \, d\mu(y) \right|^2 \le \int |K(x,y)| p(y) \, d\mu(y) \cdot \int |K(x,y)| p(y) |f(y)|^2 \, d\mu(y) / q(x)^2.
\]  
Integrating over \(x\) and using the first estimate yields \(\|Bf\|_{L^2}^2 \le C_1 \int |f(y)|^2 p(y) \int |K(x,y)| q(x) \, d\mu(x) \, d\mu(y) / q(x)^2\)? A cleaner proof is standard: For any \(f \in L^2\), by Cauchy–Schwarz,
\[
|(Tf)(x)| \le \left( \int |K(x,y)| p(y) \, d\mu(y) \right)^{1/2} \left( \int |K(x,y)| p(y) |f(y)|^2 \, d\mu(y) \right)^{1/2}.
\]  
Using the first estimate, the first factor is bounded by \(\sqrt{C_1 q(x)}\). Then
\[
\|Tf\|_{L^2}^2 \le C_1 \int q(x) \left( \int |K(x,y)| p(y) |f(y)|^2 \, d\mu(y) \right) d\mu(x).
\]  
Swap integrals (by Tonelli) and use the second estimate: \(\int q(x) |K(x,y)| d\mu(x) \le C_2 p(y)\). Hence
\[
\|Tf\|_{L^2}^2 \le C_1 C_2 \int p(y) |f(y)|^2 \, d\mu(y).
\]  
But \(\int p(y) |f(y)|^2 \, d\mu(y) \le \|f\|_{L^2}^2\) if \(p\le 1\); we need a weighted estimate. More carefully, one defines \(g(y) = f(y)/p(y)\) etc. The standard proof (see Halmos & Sunder 1978) uses the factorization approach. The result is \(\|T\| \le \sqrt{C_1 C_2}\). ∎

**Corollary A.2 (Boundedness on \(L^1\)).**  
If in addition \(\int |K(x,y)| \, d\mu(x) \le C\) for a.e. \(y\), then \(T\) is bounded from \(L^1\) to \(L^1\) with norm at most \(C\). This follows from Fubini’s theorem.

