## Appendix B: Geometric Phase and Holonomy Interpretation

We present a speculative geometric analogy linking the order‑sensitivity index to Berry‑type holonomy. This section is not essential for the rigorous proofs but provides intuition.

Let \(\Lambda\) be a smooth parameter manifold, and for each \(\lambda \in \Lambda\) let \(\Phi_\lambda\) be a CP unital map. Fix a reference state \(\rho_0\). Define \(\rho(\lambda) = \mathcal{R}_{\Phi_\lambda}(\rho_0)\). Consider a purification \(|\psi(\lambda)\rangle\) of \(\rho(\lambda)\). The Berry connection is \(A_\mu = \langle \psi | \partial_\mu \psi \rangle\), with curvature \(F_{\mu\nu} = \partial_\mu A_\nu - \partial_\nu A_\mu\).

Now take two maps \(\Phi_1, \Phi_2\) corresponding to parameters \(\lambda_1, \lambda_2\). The composition \(\mathcal{R}_{\Phi_1}\mathcal{R}_{\Phi_2}\) can be interpreted as first moving from the identity to \(\Phi_2\) then to \(\Phi_1\), while the reverse order corresponds to the opposite path. The difference between the two compositions is related to the holonomy around the closed loop. For infinitesimal parameters, the holonomy is proportional to the commutator of the generators, giving \(\mathcal{I} \approx \|[\mathcal{L}_1,\mathcal{L}_2](\rho)\|_1\). This is consistent with the BCH expansion.

A rigorous treatment would require a family of CP maps that are induced by adiabatic changes of a Hamiltonian; such a construction is possible in finite dimensions but is beyond our scope. We therefore treat this as a heuristic analogy.

