## Appendix F: Finite‑Rank Approximation for Infinite‑Dimensional Kernels

In infinite dimensions, we can approximate a CP map \(\Phi\) by finite‑rank projections. Let \(P_N\) be a sequence of finite‑dimensional projections converging strongly to the identity. Define \(\Phi_N = P_N \Phi P_N\). Then \(\Phi_N\) are finite‑dimensional CP maps. For any state \(\rho\), the sequence \(\Phi_N(\rho)\) converges weakly to \(\Phi(\rho)\). The commutativity criterion for \(\Phi\) can be tested on the finite‑dimensional approximations. If \([\mathcal{L}_N^{(1)},\mathcal{L}_N^{(2)}] \to 0\) in norm as \(N\to\infty\), we say the generators commute in the limit. This provides a practical way to verify non‑commutativity in continuous models by discretisation. The approximation is justified by Arveson’s extension theorem (1969) and Stinespring’s dilation theorem (1955), which guarantee that CP maps can be approximated by finite‑dimensional CP maps in the point‑weak* topology.

